></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use">Use</h2><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Use"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Whips are generally used on animals to provide directional guidance or t=
o encourage movement. Some whips are designed to control animals by imparti=
ng <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discomfort" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Discomfort">discomfort</a> by tapping or <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pain" title=3D"Pain">pain</a> by a full-force strike tha=
t produces <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pain_compliance" title=
=3D"Pain compliance">pain compliance</a>. Some whips provide guidance by th=
e use of sound, such as cracking of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Bullwhip" title=3D"Bullwhip">bullwhip</a>. Other uses of whips are to p=
rovide a visual directional cue by extending the reach and visibility of th=
e human arm.
</p><p>In modern times, the pain stimulus is still used in some animal trai=
ning, and is permitted in many fields, including most <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equestrianism" title=3D"Equestrianism">equestrianism</a=
> disciplines, some of which mandate carrying a whip. The whip can be a vit=
al tool to back up <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riding_aids" ti=
tle=3D"Riding aids">riding aids</a> when applied correctly, particularly wh=
en initial commands are ignored. However, many competition governing bodies=
 limit the use of whips, and severe penalties may be in place for over-use =
of the whip, including disqualification and fines.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-1=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> Improper overuse of whips may be considered <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animal_cruelty" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anima=
l cruelty">animal cruelty</a> in some jurisdictions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note=
-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lednica_G%C3%B3rna_Siuda_Baba_=
2015-04-06_389.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uploa=
d.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Lednica_G%C3%B3rna_Siuda_Baba_=
2015-04-06_389.jpg/250px-Lednica_G%C3%B3rna_Siuda_Baba_2015-04-06_389.jpg" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"4608" data-file-height=3D"3456"></a><figcaption>Whip made=
 in Silesia, Poland, made to enhance its cracking sound, used in folk Easte=
r celebrations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siuda_Baba" titl=
e=3D"Siuda Baba">Siuda Baba</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Whip use by sound never or rarely strikes the animal; instead, a long, f=
lexible whip is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whipcracking" titl=
e=3D"Whipcracking">cracked</a> to produce a very sharp, loud sound. This us=
age also functions as a form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Op=
erant_conditioning" title=3D"Operant conditioning">operant conditioning</a>=
: most animals will flinch away from the sound instinctively, making it eff=
ective for driving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sled_dog" title=
=3D"Sled dog">sled dogs</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lives=
tock" title=3D"Livestock">livestock</a> and teams of harnessed animals like=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ox" title=3D"Ox">oxen</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mule" title=3D"Mule">mules</a>. The s=
ound is loud enough to affect multiple animals at once, making whip-crackin=
g more efficient under some circumstances. This technique can be used as pa=
rt of an escalation response, with sound being used first prior to a pain s=
timulus being applied, again as part of operant conditioning.
</p><p>Whips used without painful stimulus, as an extension of the human ha=
nd or arm, are a visual command, or to tap an animal, or to exert pressure.=
 Such use may be related to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operan=
t_conditioning" title=3D"Operant conditioning">operant conditioning</a> whe=
re the subject is conditioned to associate the whip with irritation, discom=
fort or pain, but in other cases, a whip can be used as a simple tool to pr=
ovide a cue connected to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_=
reinforcement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive reinforcement">posit=
ive reinforcement</a> for compliant behavior. In the light of modern attitu=
des towards the potential for cruelty in whips, other names have gained cur=
rency among practitioners such as whips called a "wand" or a "stick," calli=
ng the lash a "string" or a "popper".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cracking">Cracking</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Cracking"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whipcracking" title=
=3D"Whipcracking">Whipcracking</a></div>
<p>The loud sound of a whip-crack is produced by a ripple in the material o=
f whip travelling towards the tip, rapidly escalating in speed until it bre=
aches the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sound_barrier" title=3D"=
Sound barrier">speed of sound</a>, more than 30 times the speed of the init=
ial movement in the handle. The crack is thus a small <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonic_boom" title=3D"Sonic boom">sonic boom</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Whip#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  Whips were the first man-made objects to br=
eak the sound barrier.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" =
style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=
=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2019)">citation=
 needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Most stick type whips cannot make a crack by themselves, unless they=
 either have a very long lash, such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Longeing" title=3D"Longeing">longe whip</a>, or are very flexible wi=
th a moderately long lash, like certain styles of buggy whip. But any desig=
n can be banged against another object, such as leather boot, to make a lou=
d noise. Short, stiff crops often have a wide leather "popper" at the end w=
hich makes a particularly loud noise when slapped against an animal, boot, =
or other object.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types">Types</h2><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Types"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stockwhip">Stockwhip</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Stockwhip"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stockwhip" title=3D"=
Stockwhip">Stockwhip</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Stockwhip.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description">=
<img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Stock=
whip.jpg/250px-Stockwhip.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"18=
8" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1600" data-file-height=3D"1=
200"></a><figcaption>An Australian stockwhip</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bullwhip.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><=
img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Bullwh=
ip.jpg/250px-Bullwhip.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=3D"238" =
class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"583" data-file-height=3D"731">=
</a><figcaption>An Australian bullwhip</figcaption></figure>
<p>Stockwhips (or <i>stock whips</i>), including bullwhips and the Australi=
an stockwhip, are a type of single-tailed leather whip with a very long las=
h but a short handle. Stockwhips are primarily used to make a loud cracking=
 sound via special techniques that break the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Sound_barrier" title=3D"Sound barrier">sound barrier</a>, to mov=
e livestock (cattle, sheep, horses, etc.) away from the sound. It is genera=
lly not used to actually strike an animal, as it would inflict excessive pa=
in and is difficult to apply with precision.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Australian">Australian</h4>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Australian"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Australian stockwhip is often said to have originated in the English=
 hunting whip, but it has since become a distinct type of whip. Today, it i=
s used primarily by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stockman_(Aust=
ralia)" title=3D"Stockman (Australia)">stockmen</a>. Unlike the short, embe=
dded handle of a bullwhip, the stockwhip handle is not fitted inside the la=
sh and is usually longer. A stockwhip's handle is connected to the thong by=
 a joint typically made of a few strands of thick <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Leather" title=3D"Leather">leather</a> (which is called a k=
eeper). This allows the whip to hang across a stockman's arm when not being=
 used. The handles are normally longer than those of a bullwhip, being betw=
een 38 and 53&nbsp;cm (15 and 21&nbsp;in). The thong can be from 1 to 3 met=
res (3 to 10&nbsp;ft) long. Stockwhips are also almost exclusively made fro=
m tanned <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kangaroo" title=3D"Kangar=
oo">kangaroo</a> hide.
</p><p>The Australian stockwhip was shown internationally when lone rider <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Jefferys" title=3D"Steve Jeff=
erys">Steve Jefferys</a> reared his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Australian_Stock_Horse" title=3D"Australian Stock Horse">Australian Stock=
 Horse</a> and cracked the stockwhip to commence the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/2000_Summer_Olympics" title=3D"2000 Summer Olympics">200=
0 Sydney Olympic Games Opening Ceremony</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Bullwhip">Bullwhip</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Bullwhip"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullwhip" title=3D"B=
ullwhip">Bullwhip</a></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullwhip" title=3D"Bullwhip">=
bullwhip</a> consists of a handle between 20 and 30&nbsp;cm (8 and 12&nbsp;=
in) in length, and a lash composed of a braided thong between 1 and 6 metre=
s (3 and 20&nbsp;ft) long. Some whips have an exposed wooden grip, others h=
ave an intricately braided leather covered handle. Unlike the Australian st=
ock whip, the thong connects in line with the handle (rather than with a jo=
int), or even engulfs the handle entirely. At the end of the lash is the "f=
all" and cracker or popper. The fall is a single piece of leather between 2=
5 and 76&nbsp;cm (10 and 30&nbsp;in) in length. During trick shots or targe=
t work, the fall is usually the portion of the whip used to cut, strike, or=
 wrap around the target. The cracker is the portion of the whip that makes =
the loud "sonic boom" sound, but a whip without a cracker will still make a=
 sonic boom, simply not as loud.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Other">Other</h4><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Other"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tropenmuseum_Royal_Tropical_Institute_Objectn=
umber_1336-6_Zweep_van_balata.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a9/Tropenmuseum_=
Royal_Tropical_Institute_Objectnumber_1336-6_Zweep_van_balata.jpg/250px-Tro=
penmuseum_Royal_Tropical_Institute_Objectnumber_1336-6_Zweep_van_balata.jpg=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"115" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"700" data-file-height=3D"322"></a><figcaption>A whip ma=
de of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balat%C3%A1" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Balat=C3=A1">balat=C3=A1</a>, made prior to 1939</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Whip,_possibly_Native_American,_Plains,_late_=
19th_century,_50.67.38.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https=
://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Whip%2C_possibly_Nativ=
e_American%2C_Plains%2C_late_19th_century%2C_50.67.38.jpg/250px-Whip%2C_pos=
sibly_Native_American%2C_Plains%2C_late_19th_century%2C_50.67.38.jpg" decod=
ing=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"128" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-f=
ile-width=3D"1536" data-file-height=3D"785"></a><figcaption><i>Whip</i>, po=
ssibly Native American, Plains, late 19th century, horsehair and rawhide, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brooklyn_Museum" title=3D"Brooklyn =
Museum">Brooklyn Museum</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Drafting_whip.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-descripti=
on"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/80/D=
rafting_whip.JPG/250px-Drafting_whip.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" =
height=3D"29" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1914" data-file-=
height=3D"219"></a><figcaption>Drafting whip (or cattle drafter) made by Ge=
orge Woolnough, the famous "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tenter=
field,_New_South_Wales" title=3D"Tenterfield, New South Wales">Tenterfield<=
/a> Saddler"</figcaption></figure>
<p>There are other variations and lengths of stock whips. The yard whip is =
a type of smaller stockwhip. The yard whip is used on ground in cattle yard=
s and other small areas where speed and precision is needed. The yard whip =
is also used by younger children that are not strong enough to handle a lar=
ge stock whip.
</p><p>The cattle drafter (or drafting whip) is a cane or fibreglass rod wi=
th a handgrip, knob and wrist strap. The cane length is about 75&nbsp;cm (2=
&nbsp;ft 6&nbsp;in) and the flapper length is about 30&nbsp;cm (12&nbsp;in)=
 long. These whips are used in cattle yards and also when moving pigs.
</p><p>The bullock-whip was used by an Australian bullock team driver (<a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullocky" title=3D"Bullocky">bullocky<=
/a>). The thong was 2.4 to 3.0 metres (8 to 10&nbsp;ft) long, or more, and =
often made of greenhide. A long handle was cut from spotted gum or another =
native tree and was frequently taller than the bullock driver's shoulder. T=
he bullocky walked beside the team and kept the bullocks moving with taps f=
rom the long handle as well as using the thong as needed.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite=
_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Rose whip is another variation of the stockwhip that was pioneer=
ed in Canada in the early 19th century, though it largely fell out of use b=
y the 1880s. The Rose whips were effective in animal yards and other small =
areas. It was pioneered by an American farmer, Jack Liao<sup class=3D"nopri=
nt Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikip=
edia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliabl=
e sources. (October 2007)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>.
</p><p>The Raman whip is a similar variation of the stockwhip which closely=
 relates to the Rose whip. This variation was pioneered in the small Ontari=
o city of Hamilton in the early 20th century, though it largely fell out of=
 use by the 1920s. Raman whips were effective on horse farms, horse derbies=
, and in other rural areas. It was pioneered by the South African inventor,=
 Delaware Kumar.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cow_whip">Cow whip</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Ded=
it&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Cow whip"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Florida cow whip used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fl=
orida" title=3D"Florida">Floridian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Cowboy" title=3D"Cowboy">cowboys</a> is a two-piece unit like the stoc=
kwhip and is connected to the handle by threading two strands of the thong =
through a hollow part of a wooden handle before being tied off. The cowwhip=
 is heavier than the Australian stockwhip. Early cowwhips were made mostly =
of cowhide or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckskin_(leather)" =
title=3D"Buckskin (leather)">buckskin</a>.
</p><p>Modern cow whips are made of flat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Nylon" title=3D"Nylon">nylon</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Parachute_cord" title=3D"Parachute cord">parachute cord</a>, which, u=
nlike those made from leather, are still effective when wet. Most cowwhips =
have handles that average 41&nbsp;cm (16&nbsp;in), and thongs that average =
30&nbsp;cm (12&nbsp;in). A good cowwhip can produce a loud crack by a simpl=
e push of the handle. This can make it more convenient to use than a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullwhip" title=3D"Bullwhip">bullwhip</a=
> in a thick vegetated environment with less swinging room. The Tampa Bay W=
hip Enthusiasts give demonstrations of the Florida Cracker Cowboy in costum=
e at the annual Heritage Village Civil War Days festival, located in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Largo,_Florida" title=3D"Largo, Florida"=
>Largo, Florida</a> every year in May.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Signalwhip">Signalwhip</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Signalwhip"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Signal_whip.JPG" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/6/6b/Signal_whip.JPG/250px-Signal_whip.JPG" decoding=3D"async" widt=
h=3D"250" height=3D"219" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1203"=
 data-file-height=3D"1052"></a><figcaption>A 1.2&nbsp;m (4') signal whip wi=
th a U.S. dollar bill for size comparison</figcaption></figure>
<p>Signal whips (or signalwhips) are a type of single-tailed whip, original=
ly designed to control dog teams. A signal whip usually measures between 0.=
9 and 1.2 metres (3 and 4&nbsp;ft) in length. Signal whips and snake whips =
are similar. What distinguishes a signal whip from a snake whip is the abse=
nce of a "fall". A fall is a piece of leather attached to the end of the bo=
dy of the whip. In a snake whip, the "cracker" attaches to the fall. In a s=
ignal whip, the cracker attaches directly to the body of the whip.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Snakewhip">Snakewhip</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Snakewhip"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Snake whips (or snakewhips) are a type of single-tailed whip. The name s=
nake whip is derived from the fact that this type of whip has no handle ins=
ide and so can be curled up into a small circle which resembles a coiled sn=
ake. They were once commonly carried in the saddlebag by cowboys of the old=
 west. A full sized snake whip is usually at least 1.2 metres (4&nbsp;ft) i=
n length (excluding the fall and cracker at the tip of the whip) and around=
 one inch in diameter at the butt of the whip.
</p><p>A pocket snake whip can be curled up small enough to fit into a larg=
e pocket, and ranges in size from 0.9 to 1.8 metres (3 to 6&nbsp;ft) in len=
gth. The pocket snake whip is primarily a whip for occasional use, such as =
in loading cattle. Both of these types of snake whips are made with a leath=
er shot bag running approximately three quarters of the length of the whip.
</p><p>Blacksnakes are the traditional whips used in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Montana" title=3D"Montana">Montana</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wyoming" title=3D"Wyoming">Wyoming</a>. The bla=
cksnake has a heavy shot load extending from the butt well down the thong, =
and the whip is flexible right to the butt.  They range in size from 1.8 to=
 3.7 metres (6 to 12&nbsp;ft) in length.  Some types concentrate a load in =
the butt (often a lead ball or steel ball-bearing) to facilitate its use as=
 improvised <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blackjack_(weapon)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Blackjack (weapon)">blackjack</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Equestrian">Equestrian</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Equestrian"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-center" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Whips.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-=
description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thu=
mb/0/03/Whips.jpg/960px-Whips.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"630" height=
=3D"109" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3189" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"551"></a><figcaption>Top: A dressage whip. Bottom: a hunting crop</fig=
caption></figure>
<p>Horse whips or riding whips are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Riding_aids" title=3D"Riding aids">artificial aids</a> used by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equestrianism" title=3D"Equestrianism">equest=
rians</a> while riding, driving, or handling <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Horse" title=3D"Horse">horses</a> from the ground.  There are ma=
ny different kinds, but all feature a handle, a long, semi-flexible shaft, =
and either a popper or lash at the end, depending on use. Riding whips rare=
ly exceed 48" from handle to popper, horse whips used for ground training a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carriage" title=3D"Carriage">ca=
rriage</a> driving are sometimes longer.
</p><p>The term "whip" is the generic word for riding whips, the term "<a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riding_crop" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Riding crop">crop</a>" is more specific, referring to a short, stiff =
whip used primarily in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_rid=
ing" title=3D"English riding">English riding</a> disciplines such as <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Show_jumping" title=3D"Show jumping">sho=
w jumping</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunt_seat" title=
=3D"Hunt seat">hunt seat</a>. Some of the more common types of horse whips =
include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dressage" title=3D"Dressag=
e">Dressage</a> whips are up to 1.1 metres (43&nbsp;in) long, including las=
h or popper, and are used to refine the aids of the rider, not to hurt the =
horse. They generally ask for more impulsion, and are long enough that they=
 can reach behind the rider's leg to tap the horse while the rider still ho=
lds the reins with both hands.  The shaft is slightly flexible and tapers t=
o a fine point at the tip. A similar, but slightly longer whip is used in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saddle_seat" title=3D"Saddle seat">=
saddle seat</a> style English riding.</li></ul>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lungeing_whip.JPG" class=3D"m=
w-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/comm=
ons/thumb/8/8f/Lungeing_whip.JPG/500px-Lungeing_whip.JPG" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"340" height=3D"64" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
2373" data-file-height=3D"444"></a><figcaption>Longeing whip</figcaption></=
figure>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longeing" title=3D"Longein=
g">Longe whips</a> have a shaft about 1.2 to 1.5 metres (4 to 5&nbsp;ft) lo=
ng and a lash of equal or greater length. They are used to direct the horse=
 as it is 'moved on a circle around the person standing in the centre, a pr=
ocess known as "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longeing" title=3D=
"Longeing">longeing</a>" (<i>pronounced</i> <span class=3D"rt-commentedText=
 nowrap"><span class=3D"IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/Engli=
sh">/<span style=3D"border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"/=CB=88/: prim=
ary stress follows">=CB=88</span><span title=3D"'l' in 'lie'">l</span><span=
 title=3D"/=CA=8C/: 'u' in 'cut'">=CA=8C</span><span title=3D"'n' in 'nigh'=
">n</span><span title=3D"/d=CA=92/: 'j' in 'jam'">d=CA=92</span><span title=
=3D"/=C9=AA/: 'i' in 'kit'">=C9=AA</span><span title=3D"/=C5=8B/: 'ng' in '=
sing'">=C5=8B</span></span>/</a></span></span>) The whip is used to guide a=
nd signal direction and pace, and is not used with force against the horse.=
 Taking the place of the rider's leg aids, the positioning of the longe whi=
p in relation to the horse gives the horse signals. Occasionally, due to th=
e long lash, it may be cracked to enforce a command.</li>
<li>Driving whips for carts, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carri=
age" title=3D"Carriage">carriages</a>, and coaches have a stock about the s=
ame length as a longe whips. The lash should be long enough to reach the sh=
oulder of the forward-most horse from the driver's seat.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-hrh_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip=
#cite_note-hrh-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crop_(implement)" title=3D"C=
rop (implement)">crop</a> or "bat" has a fairly stiff stock, and is only 0.=
6=E2=80=930.8 metres (2=E2=80=932.5&nbsp;ft) in length, with a "popper" - a=
 looped flap of leather - at the end. Because it is too short to reach behi=
nd the riders leg while still holding the reins, it is most often used by t=
aking the reins in one hand and hitting the horse behind the rider's leg, u=
sing the crop, held in the other hand. Less often, it may be used to tap th=
e horse on the shoulder as a simple reminder to the animal that the rider i=
s carrying it. It is to back up the leg aids, when the horse is not moving =
forward, or occasionally as a disciplinary measure (such as when a horse re=
fuses or runs out on a jump).  Crops or bats are most commonly seen in spor=
ts such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Show_jumping" title=3D"=
Show jumping">show jumping</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hu=
nt_seat" title=3D"Hunt seat">hunt seat</a> style <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/English_riding" title=3D"English riding">English riding</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horse_racing" title=3D"Horse raci=
ng">horse racing</a>, and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodeo=
" title=3D"Rodeo">rodeo</a> speed sports such as <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Barrel_racing" title=3D"Barrel racing">barrel racing</a>.</l=
i>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fox_hunting" title=3D"Fox hu=
nting">hunting</a> whip is not precisely a horse whip, though it is carried=
 by a mounted rider. It has a stock about the same length as a crop, except=
 its "stock" is stiff, not flexible. On one end of the stock it has a lash =
that is ~1&nbsp;m in length, on the other end it has a hook, which is used =
to help the rider open and close gates while out <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Fox_hunting" title=3D"Fox hunting">fox hunting</a>. The hunt=
ing whip is <i>not</i> intended to be used on the horse, but rather the las=
h is there to remind the hounds to stay away from the horse's hooves, and i=
t can also be used as a communication device to the hounds.</li>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quirt" title=3D"Quirt">quirt=
</a> is a short, flexible piece of thickly braided leather with two wide pi=
eces of leather at the end, which makes a loud crack when it strikes an ani=
mal or object.  They inflict more noise than pain. Quirts are occasionally =
carried on horses used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_=
riding" title=3D"Western riding">western riding</a> disciplines, but becaus=
e the action of a quirt is slow, they are not used to correct or guide the =
horse, but are more apt to be used by a rider to reach out and strike at an=
imals, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cattle" title=3D"Ca=
ttle">cattle</a> that are being herded from horseback.</li></ul>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plaited_show_cane.JPG" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/0/05/Plaited_show_cane.JPG/500px-Plaited_show_cane.JPG" deco=
ding=3D"async" width=3D"340" height=3D"35" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-f=
ile-width=3D"2074" data-file-height=3D"216"></a><figcaption>A plaited show =
cane</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li>A show cane is a short, stiff cane that may be plain, leather cover=
ed, or covered with braided leather. Traditional canes are made from a stic=
k of holly, cherry or birch wood, which is dressed and polished. They are r=
arely used now except in formal show hacking events.</li></ul>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudyard_Kipling" title=3D"Rudya=
rd Kipling">Rudyard Kipling</a>'s short story <i>Garm - a Hostage</i> menti=
ons a long whip used by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equestri=
anism" title=3D"Equestrianism">horseback rider</a> in India to defend an ac=
companying pet dog from risk of attack by native <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Pariah_dog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pariah dog">paria=
h dogs</a>.  This probably was a hunting whip.
</p><p>In Victorian literature cads and bounders are depicted as being hors=
ewhipped or threatened with horsewhipping for seduction of young women or b=
reach of promise (to marry)<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-F=
act" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span t=
itle=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2014)">ci=
tation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>, usually by her brothers or father<sup =
class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap=
;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" =
title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs referen=
ces to reliable sources. (October 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</s=
up>. Examples are found in the works of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Benjamin_Disraeli" title=3D"Benjamin Disraeli">Benjamin Disraeli</a><=
sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:no=
wrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_need=
ed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs ref=
erences to reliable sources. (October 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>=
]</sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Trollope" titl=
e=3D"Anthony Trollope">Anthony Trollope</a> who includes such a scene in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Thorne" title=3D"Doctor Thorn=
e">Doctor Thorne</a>. It is also mentioned, though not depicted, in comic n=
ovels by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evelyn_Waugh" title=3D"Ev=
elyn Waugh">Evelyn Waugh</a><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-=
Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span =
title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2014)">c=
itation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/P.G._Wodehouse" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P.G. Wodehouse">P.G. =
Wodehouse</a><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"=
white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia=
:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This c=
laim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2014)">citation needed<=
/span></a></i>]</sup>. As late as the 1970s the historian <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desmond_Seward" title=3D"Desmond Seward">Desmond Se=
ward</a> was reported by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daily=
_Telegraph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Daily Telegraph">Daily Telegraph=
</a> to have been threatened with horsewhipping for besmirching the reputat=
ion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_III" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Richard III">Richard III</a> in a biography<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to rel=
iable sources. (October 2014)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Buggy_whip_and_coachwhip">B=
uggy whip and coachwhip</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Buggy whip and coachwhip"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A buggy whip is a horsewhip with a long stiff shaft and a relatively sho=
rt lash used for driving a horse harnessed to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Buggy_(carriage)" title=3D"Buggy (carriage)">buggy</a> or oth=
er small open <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carriage" title=3D"C=
arriage">carriage</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Failing_6-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-Failing-6"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> A coachwhip, usually provided with a long lash, is used in driving a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coach_(carriage)" title=3D"Coach (car=
riage)">coach</a> with horses in front of other horses. Though similar whip=
s are still manufactured for limited purposes, the buggy whip industry as a=
 discernible economic entity ceased to exist with the introduction of the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Automobile" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Automobile">automobile</a>, and is cited in <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economics</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marketing" title=3D"Marketing">marketing<=
/a> as an example of an industry ceasing to exist because its <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_niche" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ma=
rket niche">market niche</a>, and the need for its product, disappears.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Failing_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-Failing-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cat_o'_nine_tails"><span id=
=3D"Cat_o.27_nine_tails"></span>Cat o' nine tails</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
14" title=3D"Edit section: Cat o' nine tails"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cat_o%27_nine_tails"=
 title=3D"Cat o' nine tails">Cat o' nine tails</a></div>
<p>The <b>cat o' nine tails</b> is a type of multi-tailed whip that origina=
ted as an implement for severe <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phy=
sical_punishment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Physical punishment">physi=
cal punishment</a>, notably in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Royal_Navy" title=3D"Royal Navy">Royal Navy</a> and Army of the United Kin=
gdom, and also as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judicial_corpo=
ral_punishment" title=3D"Judicial corporal punishment">judicial punishment<=
/a> in Britain and some other countries. The cat is made up of nine <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot" title=3D"Knot">knotted</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leather" title=3D"Leather">thongs</a> of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotton" title=3D"Cotton">cotton</a=
> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rope" title=3D"Rope">cord</a>, a=
bout 0.8 metres (<span class=3D"frac">2<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><spa=
n class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>&nbsp;f=
t) long, designed to lacerate the skin and cause intense pain. It tradition=
ally has nine thongs as a result of the manner in which rope is <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Braid" title=3D"Braid">plaited</a>. Thinner r=
ope is made from three strands of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Yarn" title=3D"Yarn">yarn</a> plaited together, and thicker rope from three=
 strands of thinner rope plaited together. To make a cat o' nine tails, a r=
ope is unravelled into three small ropes, each of which is unravelled again=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Weapons">Weapons</h3><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Weapons"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ming_whip,_blade,_and_truncheon.jpg" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/co=
mmons/thumb/0/08/Ming_whip%2C_blade%2C_and_truncheon.jpg/250px-Ming_whip%2C=
_blade%2C_and_truncheon.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"167=
" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3888" data-file-height=3D"25=
92"></a><figcaption>Hard whip of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
ing_dynasty" title=3D"Ming dynasty">Ming dynasty</a> (top and bottom)</figc=
aption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bian_(weapon)" titl=
e=3D"Bian (weapon)">Bian (weapon)</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Chain_whip" title=3D"Chain whip">Chain whip</a></div>
<p>The <b>Bian</b> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traditional_Ch=
inese_characters" title=3D"Traditional Chinese characters">Chinese</a>: <sp=
an lang=3D"zh-Hant">=E9=9E=AD</span>; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pinyin" title=3D"Pinyin">pinyin</a>: <i><span lang=3D"zh-Latn">Bi=C4=81=
n</span></i>; <abbr title=3D"Literal translation"><small>lit.</small></abbr=
> 'Whip'), also known as <b>Chinese whip</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-whip_7-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-=
whip-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> or <b>hard whip</b>, is a type of tubular-shaped <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Club_(weapon)" title=3D"Club (weapon)">cl=
ub</a> or rod <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weapon" title=3D"Wea=
pon">weapon</a> designed to inflict blunt damage with a whipping motion. A =
typical hard whip is made with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Met=
al" title=3D"Metal">metal</a> and has a length of around 90 <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centimetres" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Centi=
metres">centimetres</a>. Bamboo node-like protrusions are attached to the w=
eapon body at regular intervals to reduce the contact surface and enhance t=
he striking effect. The whip is stiff and does not bend. It weighs 7 or 8 <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kilogram" title=3D"Kilogram">kilogr=
ams</a>. The weapon is used mainly on horseback with one hand, sometimes wi=
th two whips in both hands.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-weapon_8-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-weapon-8"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>The <b>chain whip</b>, also known as the <b>soft whip</b>,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-soft_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Whip#cite_note-soft-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Weapon" title=3D"Weapon">weapon</a> used in some <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_martial_arts" title=3D"Chinese martial ar=
ts">Chinese martial arts</a>, particularly traditional <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_martial_arts" title=3D"Chinese martial arts">C=
hinese disciplines</a>, in addition to modern and traditional <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wushu_(term)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wu=
shu (term)">wushu</a>. It consists of several metal rods, which are joined =
end-to-end by rings to form a flexible chain. Generally, the whip has a han=
dle at one end and a metal dart, used for slashing or piercing an opponent,=
 at the other. A cloth flag is often attached at or near the dart end of th=
e whip and a second flag may cover the whip's handle.
</p><p>According to the book <i>The Chain Whip</i>, a whip in Chinese histo=
rical text may refer to either the soft whip or the hard whip due to an amb=
iguity in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_language" ti=
tle=3D"Chinese language">Chinese language</a>. "Both the hard whip and the =
soft whip can both be referred to simply as <i>whip</i> (=E9=9E=AD) in Chin=
ese."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-soft_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-soft-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Qilinbian">Qilinbian</h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWhip&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Qilinbian"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:QilinWhip.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description">=
<img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/Qilin=
Whip.jpg/250px-QilinWhip.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"18=
8" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4000" data-file-height=3D"3=
000"></a><figcaption>Qilinbian</figcaption></figure>
<p>Qilinbian (=E9=BA=92=E9=BA=9F=E9=9E=AD, literally meaning "unicorn whip"=
) is a metal whip invented in China in the late 1900s. The 15&nbsp;cm handl=
e is made from a steel chain wrapped with leather. The lash is made of stee=
l rods decreasing in size linked by progressively smaller steel rings. Lash=
 varies between 150&nbsp;cm and 180&nbsp;cm and is attached to a fall and a=
 cracker. Total weight is 1=E2=80=932&nbsp;kg. It is used for physical exer=
cise and in performances.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Animal_morphology">Animal m=
orphology</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DWh=
ip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Animal morpho=
logy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>Some organisms exhibit whip-like appendages in their physiology:
Many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicellular" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Unicellular">unicellular</a> organisms and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spermatozoa" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spermat=
ozoa">spermatozoa</a> have one or two whip-like <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Flagella" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Flagella">flagella</=
a>, which are used for propulsion. "Flagellum" is <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"Latin">Latin</a> for "whip".
</p><p>The tails of some large <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liz=
ard" title=3D"Lizard">lizards</a> (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Iguana" title=3D"Iguana">iguanas</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Monitor_lizard" title=3D"Monitor lizard">monitor lizards</a>) =
are used and optimized for whipping, and larger lizards can seriously injur=
e a human with a well-placed strike.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-11"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> The biological names of some lizards reference this with the terms <i>Mas=
tigo-</i> or <i>-mastix</i>, which derive from the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Greek_language" title=3D"Greek language">Greek</a> term fo=
r "whip".
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip_snake_(disambiguat=
ion)" class=3D"mw-redirect mw-disambig" title=3D"Whip snake (disambiguation=
)">whip snakes</a> are so-called from their physical resemblance, and were =
associated with myths that they could whip with their body in self-defense,=
 since proven false.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uropygi" title=3D"Uropygi">=
Uropygi</a> arachnids are also known as "whip scorpions" due to the shape o=
f their tails.
</p><p>It has been proposed that some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Sauropod" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sauropod">sauropod</a> dinosau=
rs could crack the ends of their tails like coach whips as a sound signal, =
as well as a form of defense against any attackers. Newer, more sophisticat=
ed models, however, suggest that while the tails of some <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diplodocidae" title=3D"Diplodocidae">Diplodocid</a> =
Dinosaurs could be used as whips, they likely would not have been able to b=
reak the sound barrier.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whip#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_popular_culture">In popu=
lar culture</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Whip&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: In popular =
culture"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>The whip is widely=E2=80=94if only situationally=E2=80=94portrayed acros=
s many avenues of popular culture.  Whips have appeared in many <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartoon" title=3D"Cartoon">cartoons</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Television_show" title=3D"Television s=
how">television shows</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_g=
ame" title=3D"Video game">video games</a> (including a central role in the =
<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castlevania" title=3D"Castlevan=
ia">Castlevania</a></i> franchise), and numerous <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Feature_film" title=3D"Feature film">feature films</a>, rang=
ing from the original <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zorro" ti=
tle=3D"Zorro">Zorro</a></i> (1919) to <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Raiders_of_the_Lost_Ark" title=3D"Raiders of the Lost Ark">Raiders o=
f the Lost Ark</a></i> (1981) and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Catwoman_(film)" title=3D"Catwoman (film)">Catwoman</a></i> (2004).
</p><p>The popular investigative-entertainment program <i><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MythBusters" title=3D"MythBusters">MythBusters</a><=
/i> tested the various capabilities of whips shown in the film <i>Raiders o=
f the Lost Ark</i> during <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MythBust=
ers_(2015_season)#Episode_224_.E2.80.93_.22The_Busters_of_the_Lost_Myths.22=
" title=3D"MythBusters (2015 season)">"The Busters of the Lost Myths"</a> e=
pisode. With exact trained usage, the show demonstrated that it is possible=
 to disarm a pistol-wielding opponent with a long whip strike. The episode =
also demonstrates that a wood log, with sufficient friction, could be used =
as an overhang to grapple with a whip, swing across a chasm and neatly dise=
ngage. Using a high-speed camera they were also able to verify that the tip=
 of a whip can break the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sound_bar=
rier" title=3D"Sound barrier">speed of sound</a>.
</p><p>In the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherlock_Holmes" =
title=3D"Sherlock Holmes">Sherlock Holmes</a></i> series of stories by <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_Arthur_Conan_Doyle" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Sir Arthur Conan Doyle">Sir Arthur Conan Doyle</a>, Holmes=
 occasionally carries a <i>loaded</i> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hunting_crop" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hunting crop">hunting crop=
</a> as his favorite weapon. (For example, see "<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/The_Adventure_of_the_Six_Napoleons" title=3D"The Adventure of=
 the Six Napoleons">The Adventure of the Six Napoleons</a>".) Such crops we=
re sold at one time. Loading refers to the practice of filling the shaft an=
d head with heavy metal (e.g., steel, lead) to provide some heft.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Whip#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
